function onLoad()
    for _, obj in ipairs(getAllObjects()) do
        if obj.hasTag('Static') or obj.hasTag('Table') then
            obj.interactable = false
            obj.drag_selectable = false
        end
    end
end

end

ObjectStates.Name: Custom_Assetbundle
ObjectStates.LuaScript:
--Announces when time runs out with a broadcast/chat message. (true or false)
announceToggle = false

--The colors the tool is, if fadeout mode is on (in r,g,b format, 0-1)
fadeoutColor_start = {1, 1, 1}
fadeoutColor_end = {0.1, 0.1, 0.1}

function onPlayerTurn(player, previous_player)
    self.flip()
end

--Runs whenever game is saved/autosaved
function onSave()
    local data_to_save = {
        cr=countdownRemaining,
        cg=countdownGoal,
        rof=resetOnFlip,
        pc=pauseCountdown,
        ft=fadeToggle,
    }
    saved_data = JSON.encode(data_to_save)
    --saved_data = "" --Remove -- at start + save to clear save data
    return saved_data
end

--Runs when game is loaded
function onLoad(saved_data)
    --Loads the tracking for if the game has started yet
    if saved_data ~= "" then
        local loaded_data = JSON.decode(saved_data)
        countdownRemaining = loaded_data.cr
        countdownGoal = loaded_data.cg
        resetOnFlip = loaded_data.rof
        pauseCountdown = loaded_data.pc
        fadeToggle = loaded_data.ft
    else
        countdownGoal = 10
        countdownRemaining = countdownGoal
        resetOnFlip = true
        pauseCountdown = false
        fadeToggle = true
    end

    --Establish color offset, how much needs to be added to fadeoutColor_start
    fadeoutColor_offset = {
        fadeoutColor_start[1]-fadeoutColor_end[1],
        fadeoutColor_start[2]-fadeoutColor_end[2],
        fadeoutColor_start[3]-fadeoutColor_end[3],
    }

    --Tracks if tool was upright based on its current memory
    currentlyUp = true
    if upsideDown() then currentlyUp = false end

    createDisplayButtons()
    createFunctionButtons()
    createTimeInputs()
end



--Countdown Handling



--Start Countdown
function onCollisionEnter(collision_info)
    function onCollisionEnter_routine()
        --Avoids an error on startup
        if currentlyUp == nil then return end
        --Check if the tool's rotation match's its current memory of what it was
        if upsideDown() and currentlyUp or not upsideDown() and not currentlyUp then
            --Toggle which way is "up" for the current status
            currentlyUp = not currentlyUp
            --Kill any currently running coroutine and wait for it to be exectued
            if countdownRunning then
                killCountdown = true
                while killCountdown do
                    coroutine.yield(0)
                end
            end
            --Determine countdown amount based off of countdown mode
            if resetOnFlip then
                countdownRemaining = countdownGoal
            else
                countdownRemaining = countdownGoal - countdownRemaining
                if countdownRemaining == 0 then
                    countdownRemaining = countdownGoal
                end
            end

            --Initate countdown
            startLuaCoroutine(self, "countdown_routine")
        end
        return 1
    end
    startLuaCoroutine(self, "onCollisionEnter_routine")
end

--Runs countdown
function countdown_routine()
    countdownRunning = true
    local startTime = os.time()
    rotateDisplayButtons()
    while countdownRemaining > 0 do
        --Perform countdown step for this frame of the game
        local timeDelta = os.time() - startTime
        countdownRemaining = countdownRemaining - timeDelta
        updateDisplayButtons()
        startTime = os.time()
        --Perform color change step
        if fadeToggle then
            --fadeoutColor_start
            --fadeoutColor_end
            percentLeft = countdownRemaining / countdownGoal
            local r = fadeoutColor_end[1] + (fadeoutColor_offset[1] * percentLeft)
            local g = fadeoutColor_end[2] + (fadeoutColor_offset[2] * percentLeft)
            local b = fadeoutColor_end[3] + (fadeoutColor_offset[3] * percentLeft)
            self.setColorTint({r,g,b})
        end

        coroutine.yield(0)

        --Stall routine until pause is removed or it is killed
        while pauseCountdown do
            startTime = os.time()
            coroutine.yield(0)
            if killCountdown then break end
        end
        --Kills coroutine on-demand
        if killCountdown then
            killCountdown = nil
            countdownRunning = false
            return 1
        end
    end

    if announceToggle then broadcastToAll("Time's Up!", {1,1,1}) end
    self.AssetBundle.playTriggerEffect(0)
    countdownRunning = false
    return 1
end

--Reset and Pause



--Pauses countdown (countdown cannot continute until reset or unpaused)
function click_pause()
    pauseCountdown = not pauseCountdown
    pauseCountdownToggle()
end

--Resets tool
function click_reset()
    if countdownRunning then
        killCountdown = true
    end
    pauseCountdown = false
    pauseCountdownToggle()
    countdownRemaining = countdownGoal
    updateDisplayButtons()
end

function pauseCountdownToggle()
    if pauseCountdown then
        for i=0,3 do
            self.editButton({index=i, font_color={0.5,0.5,0.5}})
        end
    else
        for i=0,3 do
            self.editButton({index=i, font_color={1,1,1}})
        end
    end
end





--Settings buttons/inputs



--toggles between hourglass mode and reset mode
function click_toggleMode()
    resetOnFlip = not resetOnFlip

    --Mode toggle (hourglass or reset on flip)
    local label = string.char(8987)
    local tooltip = "[b]Hourglass Mode:[/b] Flipping timer over will 'reverse' the countdown."
    if resetOnFlip then
        label = string.char(8630)
        tooltip = "[b]Reset Mode:[/b] Flipping timer over will restart the countdown."
    end
    self.editButton({index=8, label=label, tooltip=tooltip})
    self.editButton({index=9, label=label, tooltip=tooltip})
end

--Toggles between announcing or not
function click_fadeToggle()
    fadeToggle = not fadeToggle

    --Update buttons
    local label = string.char(9788)
    local tooltip = "[b]Fadeout Mode Disabled[/b]\nThe color of the timer will not change."
    if fadeToggle then
        label = string.char(9790)
        tooltip = "[b]Fadeout Mode Enabled[/b]\nThe color of the timer will fade during countdown."
    end
    self.editButton({index=10, label=label, tooltip=tooltip})
    self.editButton({index=11, label=label, tooltip=tooltip})
end

--Handles inputting of new time
function input_time(_, color, inputString, stillEditing)
    if not stillEditing then
        local inputNum = tonumber(inputString)
        if type(inputNum) == "number" and inputNum ~= countdownGoal then
            countdownGoal = inputNum
            click_reset()
            printToAll(Player[color].steam_name .. " has updated the digital hourglass's time to "..countdownGoal.." seconds.", stringColorToRGB(color))
        else
            --Here in case I decide I want to broadcast an error for a blank timer
        end
        self.clearInputs()
        createTimeInputs()
    end
end








--Information finding and formatting



--Determines if this object is upside down (using rotation values)
function upsideDown()
    if self.getRotationValue() == "Digital Hourglass " then
        return true
    else
        return false
    end
end

--Formats seconds into readable time format
function formatSecondsForCountdown(seconds)
    local seconds = math.ceil(seconds)
    local hours = math.floor(seconds / 3600)
    local minutes = math.floor((seconds / 60) % 60)
    local seconds = seconds % 60

    s = ""
    if hours > 0 then
        minutes = string.format("%02d", minutes)
        seconds = string.format("%02d", seconds)
        s = hours .. ":" .. minutes .. ":" .. seconds
    else
        seconds = string.format("%02d", seconds)
        s = minutes .. ":" .. seconds
    end

    return s
end

-- Get real string lenght per char table
function getStringUnitWidth(str)
    local len = 0
    for i = 1, #str do
        local c = str:sub(i,i)
        if ref_charUnitWidth[c] then
            len = len + ref_charUnitWidth[c]
        else
            len = len + ref_charUnitWidth.avg
        end
    end
    return len
end



--Button creation



--Places the time numbers on the 4 faces
function createDisplayButtons()
    --Format time for display
    local cd_format = formatSecondsForCountdown(countdownRemaining)

    --Adjust font size if needed
    local font_size = 300
    if getStringUnitWidth(cd_format) > 10000 then font_size = 200 end

    --Adjust font color if needed
    local font_color = {1,1,1}
    if pauseCountdown then font_color = {0.5,0.5,0.5} end

    --Adjust rotation for if it is flipped or not
    local rot_offset = 0
    if upsideDown() then rot_offset = 180 end

    --Create 4 faces
    self.createButton({
        label=cd_format, click_function="n/a", function_owner=self,
        position={0,0,0.85}, height=0, width=0, font_size=font_size,
        font_color=font_color, rotation=ref_faceRotation[upsideDown()][1]
    })
    self.createButton({
        label=cd_format, click_function="n/a", function_owner=self,
        position={0,0,-0.85}, height=0, width=0, font_size=font_size,
        font_color=font_color, rotation=ref_faceRotation[upsideDown()][2]
    })
    self.createButton({
        label=cd_format, click_function="n/a", function_owner=self,
        position={-0.85,0,0}, height=0, width=0, font_size=font_size,
        font_color=font_color, rotation=ref_faceRotation[upsideDown()][3]
    })
    self.createButton({
        label=cd_format, click_function="n/a", function_owner=self,
        position={0.85,0,0}, height=0, width=0, font_size=font_size,
        font_color=font_color, rotation=ref_faceRotation[upsideDown()][4]
    })
end



function updateDisplayButtons()
    --Format time for display
    local cd_format = formatSecondsForCountdown(countdownRemaining)
    local currentButtonData = self.getButtons()[1]
    local cd_old = currentButtonData.label

    if cd_format ~= cd_old then
        --Adjust font size if needed
        local font_size = 300
        if getStringUnitWidth(cd_format) > 10000 then font_size = 200 end

        --Edit 4 faces
        for i=0, 3 do
            self.editButton({
                index=i,
                label=cd_format,
                font_size=font_size,
                --rotation=ref_faceRotation[upsideDown()][i+1]
            })
        end
    end
end

function rotateDisplayButtons()
    for i=0, 3 do
        self.editButton({
            index=i,
            rotation=ref_faceRotation[upsideDown()][i+1]
        })
    end
end

function createFunctionButtons()
    --Pause
    self.createButton({
        label="PAUSE", click_function="click_pause", function_owner=self,
        position={0,1,-0.42}, rotation={0,0,0}, height=500, width=740,
        font_size=200, font_color={0.5,0.5,0.5}, color={0.1,0.1,0.1}
    })
    self.createButton({
        label="PAUSE", click_function="click_pause", function_owner=self,
        position={0,-1,-0.42}, rotation={180,180,0}, height=500, width=740,
        font_size=200, font_color={0.5,0.5,0.5}, color={0.1,0.1,0.1}
    })

    --Reset
    self.createButton({
        label="RESET", click_function="click_reset", function_owner=self,
        position={0,1,0.3}, rotation={0,0,0}, height=200, width=740,
        font_size=140, font_color={0.5,0.5,0.5}, color={0.1,0.1,0.1}
    })
    self.createButton({
        label="RESET", click_function="click_reset", function_owner=self,
        position={0,-1,0.3}, rotation={180,180,0}, height=200, width=740,
        font_size=140, font_color={0.5,0.5,0.5}, color={0.1,0.1,0.1}
    })

    --Mode toggle (hourglass or reset on flip)
    local label = string.char(8987)
    local tooltip = "[b]Hourglass Mode:[/b] Flipping timer over will 'reverse' the countdown."
    if resetOnFlip then
        label = string.char(8630)
        tooltip = "[b]Reset Mode:[/b] Flipping timer over will restart the countdown."
    end
    self.createButton({
        label=label, click_function="click_toggleMode", function_owner=self,
        position={-0.5,1,0.72}, rotation={0,0,0}, height=160, width=160,
        font_size=140, font_color={0.5,0.5,0.5}, color={0.1,0.1,0.1},
        tooltip=tooltip
    })
    self.createButton({
        label=label, click_function="click_toggleMode", function_owner=self,
        position={0.5,-1,0.72}, rotation={180,180,0}, height=160, width=160,
        font_size=140, font_color={0.5,0.5,0.5}, color={0.1,0.1,0.1},
        tooltip=tooltip
    })

    --Announce toggle (broadcast or not broadcast when finished)
    local label = string.char(9788)
    local tooltip = "[b]Fadeout Mode Disabled[/b]\nThe color of the timer will not change."
    if fadeToggle then
        label = string.char(9790)
        tooltip = "[b]Fadeout Mode Enabled[/b]\nThe color of the timer will fade during countdown."
    end
    self.createButton({
        label=label, click_function="click_fadeToggle", function_owner=self,
        position={0.5,1,0.72}, rotation={0,0,0}, height=160, width=160,
        font_size=110, font_color={0.5,0.5,0.5}, color={0.1,0.1,0.1},
        tooltip=tooltip
    })
    self.createButton({
        label=label, click_function="click_fadeToggle", function_owner=self,
        position={-0.5,-1,0.72}, rotation={180,180,0}, height=160, width=160,
        font_size=110, font_color={0.5,0.5,0.5}, color={0.1,0.1,0.1},
        tooltip=tooltip
    })
end

--Inputs for entering time amount
function createTimeInputs()
    self.createInput({
        label="TIME", input_function="input_time", function_owner=self,
        position={0,1,0.72}, rotation={0,0,0}, alignment=3,
        height=114, width=260, font_size=80, font_color={0.5,0.5,0.5},
        color={0.1,0.1,0.1}, value=countdownGoal, validation=2, tab=1,
        tooltip="# of seconds"
    })
    self.createInput({
        label="TIME", input_function="input_time", function_owner=self,
        position={0,-1,0.72}, rotation={0,0,180}, alignment=3,
        height=114, width=260, font_size=80, font_color={0.5,0.5,0.5},
        color={0.1,0.1,0.1}, value=countdownGoal, validation=2, tab=1,
        tooltip="# of seconds"
    })
end







--Data tables



--Rotations for the 4 faces of the timer
ref_faceRotation = {
    [false] = {
        {-90, 0, 0},
        {90, 0, 180},
        {0, 90, -90},
        {0, -90, 90},
    },
    [true] = {
        {-90, 0, 180},
        {90, 0, 0},
        {0, -90, -90},
        {0, 90, 90},
    }
}

-- Char width table by Indimeco
ref_charUnitWidth = {
    ['`'] = 2381, ['~'] = 2381, ['1'] = 1724, ['!'] = 1493, ['2'] = 2381,

Galdred is a brutal, close-range brawler who relies on an overwhelmingly threatening Exceed Mode to make up for a weak early game.

14.Name: Custom_Tile
14.Description:
S2, Difficulty 4 (Advanced)
D'Janette is an immobile striker who manipulates opponent positioning to buy time for her long-term goals.

ObjectStates.Name: CardCustom
ObjectStates.LuaScript:
function onLoad()

  -- Each character panel should set its own UI elements.
  -- I am inclined to think the character panels should be cards, or possibly uninteractable cards.
  -- When any the Normals for that panel are selected, the Character Station adjusts that player's Normals setting. This probably "propagates" a signal out to each panel to update the Normals setting display.
  -- Each panel handles its own UI elements and character table.
  -- Each panel has its own Random button and its own Normals button.
  -- Each panel also registers its characters in the Character Station for use in the Random Any and Random Legal buttons (and the Bag of Lag).
  -- When a panel is hidden, its UI is uninteractable.
  -- When a character is clicked, it sends information to the Character Station.
  -- Universal Normal information is contained in the Character Station.
  -- The Character Station generates the decks/bags using information passed to it.

  playmatStation = getObjectFromGUID([[b70028]])
  characterStation = getObjectFromGUID([[1b4685]])

  decalScale = {
    x = 2.146,
    y = 3.0675,
    z = 1, }
  decalSize = 120
  --decalReferenceURL = [[https://i.imgur.com/sj2idgS.png]]
  decalReferenceURL = [[https://i.imgur.com/sP61UtR.png]]
  decalReferencePosition = { x = 0, y = 0.363, z = 0, }

    -- Apparently, using a local variable to store a common function call improves performance.
    -- This is because Lua checks "more local" names before moving to "more global" names.
    local debugLog = debugLog

    -- The code that handles the select screen is itself portable.
    -- If the GUID here is changed, it will create the select screen functionality on some other object.
    selectScreenID = self.getGUID()
    --selectScreenID = '0e101c'
    selectScreen = getObjectFromGUID(selectScreenID)

--[=[---------------------------------------------------------------------------
    These global variables are used to record a player's current selection.
    This is in preparation for implementing the match logger on this object.
--]=]
    fighterRed    = nil
    fighterBlue   = nil
    fighterOrange = nil
    fighterPurple = nil
    fighterYellow = nil
    fighterGreen  = nil

--[=[---------------------------------------------------------------------------
    These global variables are used to record which set of Normals is currently selected by any given player.
    When a player changes their Normals, this value is replaced with the name for the new Normal set (e.g., "Seventh Cross").
    "Default" has special meaning; it instructs spawnDeck() to check the "normals" value in the appropriate charTable entry.
--]=]
    normalsRed = "Default (Alternate)"
    normalsBlue = "Default (Alternate)"
    normalsOrange = "Default (Alternate)"
    normalsPurple = "Default (Alternate)"
    normalsYellow = "Default (Alternate)"
    normalsGreen = "Default (Alternate)"
    normalsWhite = "Default (Alternate)"
    normalsPink = "Default (Alternate)"
    normalsTeal = "Default (Alternate)"
    normalsBrown = "Default (Alternate)"
    normalsBlack = "Default (Alternate)"

--[=[---------------------------------------------------------------------------
    These global variables are used by "onObjectSearchStart", "onObjectSearchEnd", and "onObjectDestroy".
    When a player starts searching an object, the nil value is replaced with that object's GUID.
    When they finish searching it and/or when it's destroyed, the value is cleared.
    If the value is nil when the player clicks a select screen button, that click is ignored.
    The point of this is to prevent clicks from passing through the on-screen search window in TTS,
    since scripted UI elements actually can catch clicks through TTS' built-in UI elements.
--]=]
    activeSearchRed = nil
    activeSearchBlue = nil
    activeSearchYellow = nil
    activeSearchGreen = nil
    activeSearchOrange = nil
    activeSearchPurple = nil

--[=[---------------------------------------------------------------------------
    normalsSheets keys are names of Normal sets.
    The suffix " (Alternate)" is used to denote an alter with the same style.
    The numeric values in the normalsSheets entries are the card IDs for the respectively-named cards.
    A Card ID indicates exactly where on an image grid the card is located.
    00 means the top-left grid location.
    01 means the grid location to the right of 00.
    So, for example, a 4x2 grid will have:
      00 01 02 03
      04 05 06 07
    All of the images I've uploaded use the exact same layout.
--]=]
    normalsSheets = {}
    normalsSheets["Red Horizon"] = { Normals = { suffix = [[ (N)]], gridWidth = "4", gridHeight = "2",
      faceURL = "https://i.imgur.com/3wJKVis.jpg",

markerScript = [===[
function onDrop(player_color)
  local myRotation = self.getRotation()
  local myPosition = self.getPosition()
  local newY = myRotation[2]
  local modY = 0
  local rotate = false

  if player_color == "Red" or player_color == "Orange" or player_color == "Yellow" then
    modY = 35
  elseif player_color == "Blue" or player_color == "Purple" or player_color == "Green" then
    modY = -35
  end
  --print("test 1")

  if myRotation[2] < 60 or myRotation[2] > 300 then
    newY = 0
    rotate = true
  elseif myRotation[2] > 120 and myRotation[2] < 240 then
    newY = 180
    rotate = true
  end
  --print("test 2")

  -- center line
  if myPosition[3] > -3 and myPosition[3] < 3 then

    -- center board
    if myPosition[1] > -17 and myPosition[1] < 17 then
      newY = newY+modY

    -- larboard
    elseif myPosition[1] > -87 and myPosition[1] < -53 then
      newY = newY+modY

    -- starboard
    elseif myPosition[1] > 53 and myPosition[1] < 87 then
      newY = newY+modY

    end
  end
  --print("test 3")

  if rotate == true then
    self.setRotationSmooth({
        x = myRotation[1],
        y = newY,
        z = myRotation[3],
      }, false)
  end
end
]===]

function resetCard()
  local thisCardFaces = sansFaces
  local thisCardBodies = sansBodies
  local thisCardIcons = sansIcons

  local decalPosition = { x = 0, y = 0.4, z = 0, }
  local decalRotation = { x = 90, y = 180, z = 0, }
  local decalScale = { x = ]=====]..decalScale.x..[=====[, y = ]=====]..decalScale.y..[=====[, z = ]=====]..decalScale.z..[=====[, }
  local decalSize = ]=====]..decalSize..[=====[

  -- If the GMNotes for this card end in '.reference', it's a reference card.
  if string.match(self.getGMNotes(), '.*%.reference$') then
    table.insert(activeDecals, {
      position = { x = decalPosition.x, y = ]=====]..decalReferencePosition.y..[=====[, z = decalPosition.z, },
      rotation = decalRotation,
      scale = decalScale,
      size = decalSize,
      name = [[referenceDecal]],
      url = [[]=====]..decalReferenceURL..[=====[]],
    })
  end

  -- Randomize the face decal.
  local count = 0
  for i in ipairs(thisCardFaces) do count = count+1 end
  local faceDecal = thisCardFaces[math.random(1, count)]

  -- Randomize the body and legs decals. (They're associated with each other.)
  count = 0
  for i in ipairs(thisCardBodies) do count = count+1 end
  local bodyDecal = thisCardBodies[math.random(1, count)]

  -- Randomize the icon decal.
  count = 0
  for i in ipairs(thisCardIcons) do count = count+1 end
  local iconDecal = thisCardIcons[math.random(1, count)]

  -- If there's a face decal, add it to the list.
  if faceDecal != nil and faceDecal != [[]] then
    table.insert(activeDecals, {
      position = { x = decalPosition.x, y = 0.33, z = decalPosition.z, },
      rotation = decalRotation,
      scale = decalScale,
      size = decalSize,
      name = [[attackface]],
      url = faceDecal,
    })
  end

  -- If there's a body decal, add it to the active decal set.
  if bodyDecal.body != nil and bodyDecal.body != [[]] then
    table.insert(activeDecals, {
      position = { x = decalPosition.x, y = 0.31, z = decalPosition.z, },
      rotation = decalRotation,
      scale = decalScale,
      size = decalSize,
      name = [[attackbody]],
      url = bodyDecal.body,
    })
  end

  -- If there's a legs decal, add it to the active decal set.
  if bodyDecal.legs != nil and bodyDecal.legs != [[]] then
    table.insert(activeDecals, {
      position = { x = decalPosition.x, y = 0.32, z = decalPosition.z, },
      rotation = decalRotation,
      scale = decalScale,
      size = decalSize,
      name = [[attacklegs]],
      url = bodyDecal.legs,
    })
  end

  -- If there's an icon decal, add it to the active decal set.
  if iconDecal != nil and iconDecal != [[]] then
    table.insert(activeDecals, {
      position = { x = decalPosition.x, y = 0.325, z = decalPosition.z, },
      rotation = decalRotation,
      scale = decalScale,
      size = decalSize,
      name = [[attackicon]],
      url = iconDecal,
    })
  end

  -- Apply the decals.
  self.setDecals(activeDecals)
end -- end resetCard()

  for i in ipairs(sansCharacterBodies) do count = count+1 end

  -- If there's a face decal, add it to the active decal set.

  -- If there's a body decal, add it to the active decal set.

      rotation = decalRotationCharacter,

      size = decalSize,

    if self.getRotation()[3] < 45 or self.getRotation()[3] > 315 then

    elseif self.getRotation()[3] > 135 and self.getRotation()[3] < 225 then

    -- Repeat the loop.
    delusions()

    This allows the background image to appear clearly.

--[=[

--[=[

    Objects, buttons, and UI elements all use different scales for their position values.
      (UI elements also flip Y and Z, and apparently have an inverted sign on their X values?)
    Accordingly, rather than saving different explicit values, we can just multiply the original position value by different factors.
      (Theoretically, the X and Z factors should be exactly the same in magnitude. No idea why it seems to look better with slightly larger Z factors.)
--]=]

    imageFactor2 = -31.45 -- multiplied by position.z to generate second value in the UI element position string

--[=[---------------------------------------------------------------------------
    For every entry in charTable:
      - Add the character to the appropriate random select tables (randomBoards).
      - Add a button for the character to btnTable.
      - Add a UI element for the character to selectXMLTable.
      - If the character has a secret password, record it in passwordsTable.

    Secret passwords structure:
      - Each player has their own entry in passwordEntries.
      - - Use PlayerInstance.steam_id.
      - When a player clicks a character, its name is appended to passwordEntries.
      - When a player clicks Random Boss, their password is checked against each entry in passwordsTable.
      - - If an entry matches, override the character roll with that entry's index.
      - - After checking all entries, clear that player's entry in passwordEntries.
--]=]
    passwordEntries = {}
    passwordsTable = {}
    for charName,thisChar in pairs(charTable) do
      --debugLog{ "per-char loop: "..charName, 2, {1,1,1} }

      -- Add this character to the random table for its season.
      local season = thisChar.season
      if season != nil and randomBoards[season] != nil then
        --debugLog{ "   season: "..thisChar.season, 3, {0.3,1,1} }
        table.insert(randomBoards[season].table, charName)
      end

      -- If the character isn't godforsaken, add them to Random Any.
      if thisChar.godforsaken != true then
        table.insert(randomBoards["Any"].table, charName)
      else
        --debugLog{ "   godforsaken!", 3, {0,0,0} }
      end

      -- If the character is legal, add them to Random Legal.
      if thisChar.legal == true then
        --debugLog{ "   legal!", 3, {1.0,0.3,1.0} }
        table.insert(randomBoards["Legal"].table, charName)
      end

      -- If the character has a password, add it to passwordsTable.
      if thisChar.secretPassword != nil then
        passwordsTable[charName] = thisChar.secretPassword
      end

  --[=[   ----------------------------------------------------------------------
      Add a UI element for this character to the table which will be used to set this object's XML.
      This element displays a tooltip that shows a preview of the character.
      It's also the thing which actually catches clicks and activates the spawn function.
  --]=]
      -- Determine what border color will be used for this UI element (well, for its tooltip).
      if randomBoards[season] != nil then
        -- Prefer the character-specific entry over the season-wide entry.
        thisChar.borderColor = thisChar.borderColor or randomBoards[season].tooltipOutline
      end
      -- If there was neither a character-specific nor a season-wide entry, default to invisible.
      thisChar.borderColor = thisChar.borderColor or { 1, 1, 1, 0 }
      local borderColorString = "rgba("..thisChar.borderColor[1]..","..thisChar.borderColor[2]..","..thisChar.borderColor[3]..","..thisChar.borderColor[4]..")" or "rgba(1,1,1,0)"
      --debugLog{ "borderColorString: "..borderColorString, 3}

      -- IF there's a position for the UI element, actually set up and insert the UI element.
      if thisChar.position != nil then
        -- Insert an entry for this character into the table of buttons to be created later.
        table.insert(btnTable, {
          position = {
            x = thisChar.position.x,
            y = thisChar.position.y,
            z = thisChar.position.z,
          },
          tooltip = charName,
        })

        -- Determine this UI element's position string.
        local positionString = (imageFactor1*thisChar.position.x).." "..(imageFactor2*thisChar.position.z).." "..(imageFactor3*thisChar.position.y)

        -- If this character's tooltip backdrop should be different from usual, use it instead of the blank backdrop.
        local thisTooltip = thisChar.assetTooltip or blankTooltip

        -- Insert the element into the table.
        --debugLog{ "inserting XML for: "..thisChar.assetName, 1, {0,1,1} }
        table.insert(selectXMLTable, {-- Image element.
        tag = "Image",
        attributes = {
          id = charName,
          height = 53,
          width = 53,
          position = positionString,
          rotation = "0 0 0",
          color = "rgba(0,0.7,1,0)", -- Fully transparent by default. Change this to debug element positions.
          raycastTarget = "true",
          onClick = self.getGUID().."/uiClick_Character",
          tooltip = thisTooltip,
          tooltipTextColor = "rgba(1,1,1,0)",
          tooltipBorderColor = borderColorString,
          tooltipBackgroundColor = "rgba(1,1,1,1)",
          tooltipBackgroundImage = thisChar.assetName,
          tooltipPosition = "Above",
          tooltipOffset = "-95",
          --visibility = "Red|Blue|Yellow|Green|Orange|Purple",
          }, -- end attributes for Image
      }) -- Finish inserting XML table entry.
    end
    end -- Finish looping through charTable.

--[=[---------------------------------------------------------------------------
    For every entry in randomBoards:
      - Add a button for the random select to btnTable.
      - Add a UI element for the random select to selectXMLTable.
--]=]
    for i,thisBoard in pairs(randomBoards) do

      -- Insert an entry for this character into the table of buttons to be created later.
      table.insert(btnTable, {
        position = {
          x = thisBoard.position.x,
          y = thisBoard.position.y,
          z = thisBoard.position.z,
        },
      tooltip = thisBoard.tooltip,
      })

  --[=[   ----------------------------------------------------------------------
      Add a UI element for this random select to the table which will be used to set this object's XML.
      This element displays a tooltip that shows some kind of nifty picture.
      It's also the thing which actually catches clicks and activates the spawn function.
  --]=]
      -- Determine what border color will be used for this UI element (well, for its tooltip).
      local borderColorString = "rgba("..thisBoard.tooltipOutline[1]..","..thisBoard.tooltipOutline[2]..","..thisBoard.tooltipOutline[3]..","..thisBoard.tooltipOutline[4]..")" or "rgba(1,1,1,0)"

      -- Determine this UI element's position string.
      local positionString = (imageFactor1*thisBoard.position.x).." "..(imageFactor2*thisBoard.position.z).." "..(imageFactor3*thisBoard.position.y)

      -- Insert the element into the table.
      --debugLog{ "inserting XML for: "..randomBoards[i].assetName, 2, {1,0,1} }
      table.insert(selectXMLTable, {-- Image element.
        tag = "Image",
        attributes = {
          id = i,
          height = 53,
          width = 53,
          position = positionString,
          rotation = "0 0 0",
          color = "rgba(0,0.7,1,0)", -- Fully transparent by default. Change this to debug element positions.
          raycastTarget = "true",
          onClick = self.getGUID().."/uiClick_Random",
          tooltip = blankTooltip,
          tooltipTextColor = "rgba(1,1,1,0)",
          tooltipBorderColor = borderColorString,
          tooltipBackgroundColor = "rgba(1,1,1,1)",
          tooltipBackgroundImage = thisBoard.assetName,
          tooltipPosition = "Above",
          tooltipOffset = "-95",
          --visibility = "Red|Blue|Yellow|Green|Orange|Purple",
        }, -- end attributes for Image
      }) -- Finish inserting XML table entry.
    end -- Finish looping through randomBoards.

--[=[---------------------------------------------------------------------------
    For each of the seated player colors, create a ToggleGroup UI element visible only to them.
    This UI element is what updates the setting for their current Normals.
--]=]
    local yOffset = -190
    local xOffset = -24.38
    local xIncrement = 64.5
    for i,thisPlayer in ipairs({ "Red", "Blue", "Yellow", "Green", "Orange", "Purple", "White", "Pink", "Brown", "Teal"}) do
      --debugLog{ "Adding Normals toggle group for "..v, 1}
      local colorString = [[#FFFFFF|]]..thisPlayer..[[|#C8C8C8]]
      local invertColor = Color[thisPlayer]
      invertColor = {
        r = 1-invertColor[1],
        g = 1-invertColor[2],
        b = 1-invertColor[3],
        a = 1,}
      local invertColorString = "rgba("..invertColor.r..","..invertColor.g..","..invertColor.b..","..invertColor.a..")"

      functionString = self.getGUID().."/uiClick_Normals"
      table.insert(selectXMLTable, {-- ToggleGroup element.
      tag = "ToggleGroup",
        children = {
          { -- Toggle child
            tag = 'Toggle',
            attributes = {
              id = 'Default'..thisPlayer,
              --colors = thisPlayer..[[|#FFFFFF|C8C8C8]],
              colors = invertColorString..[[|]]..invertColorString..[[|#C8C8C8]],
              isOn = true,
              onClick = functionString,
              --onValueChanged = functionString,
              offsetXY = (xOffset-(5*xIncrement)).." "..yOffset,
            }, -- end Toggle attributes
          }, -- end Toggle
          { -- Toggle child
            tag = 'Toggle',
            attributes = {
              id = 'Red Horizon'..thisPlayer,
              colors = colorString,
              onClick = functionString,
              offsetXY = (xOffset-(4*xIncrement)).." "..yOffset,
            }, -- end Toggle attributes
          }, -- end Toggle
          { -- Toggle child
            tag = 'Toggle',
            attributes = {
              id = 'Seventh Cross'..thisPlayer,
              colors = colorString,
              onClick = functionString,
              offsetXY = (xOffset-(3*xIncrement)).." "..yOffset,
            }, -- end Toggle attributes
          }, -- end Toggle
          { -- Toggle child
            tag = 'Toggle',
            attributes = {
              id = 'Street Fighter'..thisPlayer,
              colors = colorString,
              onClick = functionString,
              offsetXY = (xOffset-(2*xIncrement)).." "..yOffset,
            }, -- end Toggle attributes
          }, -- end Toggle
          { -- Toggle child
            tag = 'Toggle',
            attributes = {
              id = 'Shovel Knight (Diverse)'..thisPlayer,
              colors = colorString,
              onClick = functionString,
              offsetXY = (xOffset-(1*xIncrement)).." "..yOffset,
            }, -- end Toggle attributes
          }, -- end Toggle
          { -- Toggle child
            tag = 'Toggle',
            attributes = {
              id = 'BlazBlue (Diverse)'..thisPlayer,
              colors = colorString,
              onClick = functionString,
              offsetXY = xOffset.." "..yOffset,
            }, -- end Toggle attributes
          }, -- end Toggle
        }, -- end children of ToggleGroup
        attributes = {
          id = 'ToggleGroup'..thisPlayer,
          height = "10",
          width = "20",
          position = "0 0 -100",
          visibility = thisPlayer,
        }, -- end attributes for ToggleGroup
      }) -- end ToggleGroup
    end -- Finish looping through the six player colors.

--[=[---------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Now, go through btnTable and create all the decorative buttons.
    Remember, these only exist so the tooltips show up properly.
    However, it seems to kick errors if you leave "click_function" empty.
--]=]
---[=[
    for i,thisButton in pairs(btnTable) do
      local scale = thisButton.scale or 1
      local pos = thisButton.position or { 0, 0, 0 }
      --debugLog{ "adding button "..i..": "..btnTable[i].tooltip, 5, {0, 1, 0} }

      selectScreen.createButton(btnParams)

function printTable(thisTable, indentation)
  local indent = indentation or [[]]
  indent = indent.." "
  local printString = [[]]
  if type(thisTable) == [[table]] then
    for key,val in pairs(thisTable) do
      if type(key) == "number" then
        printString = printString..[=[

[AAAAAA]]=]
      else
        printString = printString..[=[

[FFFFFF]]=]
      end
      printString = printString..indent..[[key: ]]..key..[=[[-], ]=]
      --printToAll(indent.."key: "..key)
      printString = printString..printTable(val, indent)
    end
  elseif type(thisTable) == [[boolean]] then
    if thisTable then
      printString = printString..[=[[00FF00]value: true[-]]=]
      --printToAll(indent.."value: true", {0,1,0})
    else
      printString = printString..[=[[FFFF00]value: false[-]]=]
      --printToAll(indent.."value: false", {1,1,0})
    end
  elseif type(thisTable) == [[nil]] then
    printString = printString..[=[[FF0000]is nil[-]]=]
  else
    --local value = thisTable or "nil"
    printString = printString..[=[[00FFFF]value: ]=]..thisTable..[=[[-]]=]
    --printToAll(indent.."value: "..thisTable, {0,1,1})
  end
  return printString
end -- end printTable

function uiClick_Normals(player, value, id)
  if _G["activeSearch"..player.color] != nil then
    return
  end
  local newAlternate = false
  if value != "-1" then
    newAlternate = true
  end
  local oldNormals = _G["normals"..player.color]
  local oldNormalsBase,oldAlternate = string.gsub(oldNormals, [[ %(Alternate%)]], [[]])
  local newValue = string.sub(id, 1, (-1*(string.len(player.color)+1)))
  debugLog{ "click_Normals clicked by "..player.color, 0, {0.6,0.6,0.6} }
  debugLog{ "  previous Normals: "..oldNormals, 2, {0.8,0.8,0.8} }
  debugLog{ "  previous Normals Base: "..oldNormalsBase, 5, {0.8,0.8,0.8}}
  debugLog{ "  value: "..value, 3}
  debugLog{ "  oldAlternate: "..oldAlternate, 3}

  -- Using the number of replacements made, determine whether the old Normals selection was alternate or not.
  if oldAlternate == 0 then
    oldAlternate = false
  else
    oldAlternate = true
  end

  -- If the new and the old selections are the same AND are both the same disposition (alternate or non), do nothing.
  if oldAlternate == newAlternate and oldNormalsBase == newValue then
    return
  end

  local invertColor = Color[player.color]
  invertColor = {
    r = 1-invertColor[1],
    g = 1-invertColor[2],
    b = 1-invertColor[3],
    a = 1,}
  local invertColorString = "rgba("..invertColor.r..","..invertColor.g..","..invertColor.b..","..invertColor.a..")"
  debugLog{ "invertColor: "..invertColorString, 2}

  -- Reset the previous Normals' corresponding toggle.
  --debugLog{ "  old Normals base name: "..oldNormals, 5, {0.9,0.9,0.9} }
  self.UI.setAttribute(oldNormalsBase..player.color, "colors", [[#FFFFFF|]]..player.color..[[|#C8C8C8]])

  -- Need to set the toggle to isOn because non-left-clicking doesn't change the toggle.
  self.UI.setAttribute(newValue..player.color, "isOn", true)
  self.UI.setAttribute(newValue..player.color, "colors", player.color..[[|]]..player.color..[[|#C8C8C8]])

  -- If left-clicking on Default or on any toggle that has an Alternate set available, indicate as much.
  if (newValue == "Default" and value == "-1") or (normalsSheets[newValue.." (Alternate)"] != nil and value == "-1") then
    player.broadcast("Normals set to "..newValue..". (Right-click instead for reskinned Normals.)", {1,1,0.6})
  end

  -- If this wasn't an ordinary left-click...
  if newAlternate == true then
    --debugLog{ "alternate detection: not equal to -1", 1}

    -- Only do something if the new Normals are Default, or if there's an Alternate version of the new Normals.
    if newValue == "Default" or normalsSheets[newValue.." (Alternate)"] != nil then

      -- Invert the color for this toggle to indicate that the Alternate mode is on.
      self.UI.setAttribute(newValue..player.color, "colors", invertColorString..[[|]]..invertColorString..[[|#C8C8C8]])

      -- Inform the player that they've enabled Alternate Normals.
      player.broadcast("Normals set to reskinned "..newValue..". (Left-click instead for classic Normals.)", invertColor)
      newValue = newValue.." (Alternate)"
    end -- end 'if newValue == Default' ...
  end -- end 'if value != "-1" then
  debugLog{ "  new Normals: "..newValue, 1, {0.8,0.8,0.8} }
  _G["normals"..player.color] = newValue
end -- end uiClick_Normals



--[=[
  getCardData({
    cardColor       = {
      r = --float,
      g = --float,
      b = --float,
      a = --float,
    },
    cardBack        = --string,
    cardDecals      = --string,
    cardDescription = --string,
    cardFace        = --string,
    cardGMNotes     = --string,
    cardMemo        = --string, -- Used for various custom "tags".
    cardNickname    = --string,
    cardID          = --string or int,
    cardScript      = --string,
    cardSnap        = --string,
    deckID          = --string or int,
    gridWidth       = --string or int,
    gridHeight      = --string or int,
    hiddenBack      = --string (like boolean),
    reference       = --string (like boolean),
    tooltip         = --string (like boolean),
    transform = {
      scaleX = --float,
      scaleY = --float,
      scaleZ = --float,
      rotX   = --float,
      rotY   = --float,
      rotZ   = --float,
    }
  }) -- returns a JSON string representing a single card
--]=]
function getCardData(params)
  local cardBack        = params.cardBack        or [[]]
  local cardColor       = params.cardColor or {}
    cardColor.r = cardColor.r or 0.713235259
    cardColor.g = cardColor.g or 0.713235259
    cardColor.b = cardColor.b or 0.713235259
    cardColor.a = cardColor.a or 1
  local cardDescription = params.cardDescription or [[]]
  local cardFace        = params.cardFace        or [[]]
  local cardID          = params.cardID          or [[00]]
  local cardGMNotes     = params.cardGMNotes     or [[]]
  local cardMemo        = params.cardMemo        or [[]]
  local cardNickname    = params.cardNickname    or [[]]
  local cardScript      = params.cardScript      or [[]]
  local cardSnap        = params.cardSnap        or [[true]]
  local cardDecals      = params.cardDecals      or {}
  local cardDecalsString  = [[
  "AttachedDecals": [
    ]]
  local deckID          = params.deckID          or [[1]]
  local gridWidth       = params.gridWidth       or [[1]]
  local gridHeight      = params.gridHeight      or [[1]]
  local hiddenBack      = params.hiddenBack      or [[true]]
  local reference       = params.reference       or [[false]]
  local tooltip         = params.tooltip         or [[false]]
  local transform       = params.transform or {}
    transform.scaleX = transform.scaleX or 1.25
    transform.scaleY = transform.scaleY or 1.0
    transform.scaleZ = transform.scaleZ or 1.25
    transform.rotX   = transform.rotX   or 0
    transform.rotY   = transform.rotY   or 0
    transform.rotZ   = transform.rotZ   or 0

  if type(hiddenBack) == "boolean" then
    if hiddenBack == true then
      hiddenBack = "true"
    else
      hiddenBack = "false"
    end
  end

--[=[
  Strings within JSON strings don't accept linebreaks or quotation marks.
  Quotation marks must be escaped with a backslash, while linebreaks must be represented as "\r\n".
  Turns out JSON has a built-in way to do this. Note that the result includes enclosing quotation marks.
--]=]
  cardDescription = JSON.encode(cardDescription)
  cardGMNotes = JSON.encode(cardGMNotes)
  cardMemo = JSON.encode(cardMemo)
  cardNickname = JSON.encode(cardNickname)
  cardScript = JSON.encode(cardScript)
  --debugLog{" cardBack: "..cardBack}
  --debugLog{"    cardColor r: "..cardColor.r}
  --debugLog{"    cardColor g: "..cardColor.g}
  --debugLog{"    cardColor b: "..cardColor.b}
  --debugLog{"    cardColor a: "..cardColor.a}
  --debugLog{" cardDescription: "..cardDescription}
  --debugLog{" cardNickname: "..cardNickname}
  --debugLog{" cardFace: "..cardFace}
  --debugLog{" cardID: "..cardID}
  --debugLog{" cardScript: "..cardScript}
  --debugLog{" deckID: "..deckID}
  --debugLog{" gridWidth: "..gridWidth}
  --debugLog{" gridHeight: "..gridHeight}
  --debugLog{" hiddenBack: "..hiddenBack}
  --debugLog{" tooltip: "..tooltip}
  --debugLog{"   transform scaleX: "..transform.scaleX}
  --debugLog{"   transform scaleY: "..transform.scaleY}
  --debugLog{"   transform scaleZ: "..transform.scaleZ}
  --debugLog{"   transform rotX: "..transform.rotX}
  --debugLog{"   transform rotY: "..transform.rotY}
  --debugLog{"   transform rotZ: "..transform.rotZ}

  local returnString = [[
  {
  "Name": "Card",
  "Transform": {
      "scaleX": ]]..transform.scaleX..[[,
      "scaleY": ]]..transform.scaleY..[[,
      "scaleZ": ]]..transform.scaleZ..[[,
      "rotX": ]]..transform.rotX..[[,
      "rotY": ]]..transform.rotY..[[,
      "rotZ": ]]..transform.rotZ..[[,
    },
  "Nickname": ]]..cardNickname..[[,
  "Description": ]]..cardDescription..[[,
  "GMNotes": ]]..cardGMNotes..[[,
  "Memo": ]]..cardMemo..[[,
  "ColorDiffuse": {
      "r": ]]..cardColor.r..[[,
      "g": ]]..cardColor.g..[[,
      "b": ]]..cardColor.b..[[,
      "a": ]]..cardColor.a..[[
    },
  "Locked": false,
  "Grid": true,
  "Snap": ]]..cardSnap..[[,
  "IgnoreFoW": false,
  "MeasureMovement": false,
  "DragSelectable": true,
  "Autoraise": true,
  "Sticky": true,
  "Tooltip": ]]..tooltip..[[,
  "GridProjection": false,
  "HideWhenFaceDown": ]]..hiddenBack..[[,
  "Hands": true,
  "CardID": ]]..deckID..cardID..[[,
  "SidewaysCard": false,
  "CustomDeck": {
  "]]..deckID..[[": {
          "FaceURL": "]]..cardFace..[[",
          "BackURL": "]]..cardBack..[[",
          "NumWidth": ]]..gridWidth..[[,
          "NumHeight": ]]..gridHeight..[[,
          "BackIsHidden": ]]..hiddenBack..[[,
          "UniqueBack": false,
          "Type": 0
        },
  },
  "LuaScript": ]]..cardScript..[[,
  "GUID": "2d01dd",]]
  local refDecal = getReferenceDecal()
  --debugLog{"reference value: "..reference, 2}
  if reference == [[true]] then
    debugLog{"applying reference", 2, {0,1,1}}
    cardDecalsString = cardDecalsString..[[
        {
          "Transform": {
            "posX": ]]..refDecal.transform.posX..[[,
            "posY": ]]..refDecal.transform.posY..[[,
            "posZ": ]]..refDecal.transform.posZ..[[,
            "rotX": ]]..refDecal.transform.rotX..[[,
            "rotY": ]]..refDecal.transform.rotY..[[,
            "rotZ": ]]..refDecal.transform.rotZ..[[,
            "scaleX": ]]..refDecal.transform.scaleX..[[,
            "scaleY": ]]..refDecal.transform.scaleY..[[,
            "scaleZ": ]]..refDecal.transform.scaleZ..[[
          },
          "ColorDiffuse": {
            "r": ]]..refDecal.color.r..[[,
            "g": ]]..refDecal.color.g..[[,
            "b": ]]..refDecal.color.b..[[,
            "a": ]]..refDecal.color.a..[[
          },
          "CustomDecal": {
            "Name": "]]..refDecal.name..[[",
            "ImageURL": "]]..refDecal.image..[[",
            "Size": ]]..refDecal.size..[[,
          }
        },
    ]]
  end
  for i,thisDecal in ipairs(cardDecals) do
    --debugLog{" decal iterator: "..i, 2}
    local decalTransform = thisDecal.transform or refDecal.transform
    local decalColor = thisDecal.color or refDecal.color
    local decalName  = thisDecal.name or refDecal.name
    local decalImage = thisDecal.image or refDecal.image
    local decalSize  = thisDecal.size or refDecal.size
    cardDecalsString = cardDecalsString..[[
        {
          "Transform": {
            "posX": ]]..decalTransform.posX..[[,
            "posY": ]]..decalTransform.posY..[[,
            "posZ": ]]..decalTransform.posZ..[[,
            "rotX": ]]..decalTransform.rotX..[[,
            "rotY": ]]..decalTransform.rotY..[[,
            "rotZ": ]]..decalTransform.rotZ..[[,
            "scaleX": ]]..decalTransform.scaleX..[[,
            "scaleY": ]]..decalTransform.scaleY..[[,
            "scaleZ": ]]..decalTransform.scaleZ..[[
          },
          "ColorDiffuse": {
            "r": ]]..decalColor.r..[[,
            "g": ]]..decalColor.g..[[,
            "b": ]]..decalColor.b..[[,
            "a": ]]..decalColor.a..[[
          },
          "CustomDecal": {
            "Name": "]]..decalName..[[",
            "ImageURL": "]]..decalImage..[[",
            "Size": ]]..decalSize..[[,
          }
        },
    ]]
  end
  if cardDecalsString != [[]] then
    cardDecalsString = cardDecalsString..[[
    ],
    ]]
    --debugLog{"cardDecalsString: "..cardDecalsString, 2}
    returnString = returnString..cardDecalsString
  end
  return returnString..[[

  },
  ]]
end

--[=[
getSubdeckData({
  deckID     = -- string or int,
  cardFace   = -- URL string,
  cardBack   = -- URL string,
  gridWidth  = -- string or int,
  gridHeight = -- string or int,
  hiddenBack = -- string (like boolean),
}) -- returns a JSON string representing CustomDeck data
--]=]
function getSubdeckData(params)
  deckID = params.deckID
  cardFace = params.cardFace
  cardBack = params.cardBack
  gridWidth = params.gridWidth
  gridHeight = params.gridHeight
  hiddenBack = params.hiddenBack

  if type(hiddenBack) == "boolean" then
    if hiddenBack == true then
      hiddenBack = "true"
    else
      hiddenBack = "false"
    end
  end

  return [[
  "]]..deckID..[[": {
          "FaceURL": "]]..cardFace..[[",
          "BackURL": "]]..cardBack..[[",
          "NumWidth": ]]..gridWidth..[[,
          "NumHeight": ]]..gridHeight..[[,
          "BackIsHidden": ]]..hiddenBack..[[,
          "UniqueBack": false,
          "Type": 0
        },
]]
--[=[ "Type" is the card corner type:
  0 = Rectangle, Rounded Corners (default)
  1 = Rectangle, Sharp Corners
  2 = Hexagon, Rounded Corners
  3 = Hexagon, Sharp Corners
  4 = Oval
--]=]
end


--[=[---------------------------------------------------------------------------
Need to document this function properly at some point.
--]=]
function spawnDeck(params)
  local debugLog        = debugLog
  local deckName        = params.deckName
  local deckDescription = params.deckDescription or charTable[deckName].deckDescription or [[]] -- Usually nil.
  local deckList        = params.deckList
  local playerReference = params.player
  local alternate       = params.alternate or false

  local playerHandTransform = Player[playerReference.color].getHandTransform() or {
    position = {
      x = xPositionOffset + selectScreen.getPosition().x,
      y = 10 + yPositionOffset + selectScreen.getPosition().y,
      z = zPositionOffset + selectScreen.getPosition().z,
    },
    rotation = selectScreen.getRotation(),
  }

  local cardColor = {}
  cardColor[1] = 0.713235259
  cardColor[2] = 0.713235259
  cardColor[3] = 0.713235259
  cardColor[4] = 1

  if charTable[deckName].borderColor != nil then
    cardColor[1] = charTable[deckName].borderColor[1] or 0.713235259
    cardColor[2] = charTable[deckName].borderColor[2] or 0.713235259
    cardColor[3] = charTable[deckName].borderColor[3] or 0.713235259
    cardColor[4] = charTable[deckName].borderColor[4] or 1
  end

  -- Added for April Fool's 2021.
  local foilRoll = math.random(1,40)
  if foilRoll == 1 then
    playerReference.print([[ [9BFF37]A [-][37FF37]r[-][37FF9B]a[-][37FFFF]r[-][379BFF]e [-][3737FF]f[-][9B37FF]o[-][FF37FF]i[-][FF379B]l [-][FF3737]s[-][FF9B37]l[-][FFFF37]e[-][9BFF37]e[-][37FF37]v[-][37FF9B]e[-][37FFFF]d[-][379BFF] d[-][3737FF]e[-][9B37FF]c[-][FF37FF]k[-]![b] Everything's gotten brighter!]], {0.8,0.8,0.8})
    cardColor[1] = 5+(cardColor[1]*10)
    cardColor[2] = 5+(cardColor[2]*10)
    cardColor[3] = 5+(cardColor[3]*10)
  end

  -- Set the attack back to the character's unique attack back, or to the default card back if there isn't one.
  local backURL = charTable[deckName].attackBack or [[https://i.imgur.com/igYZhPh.png]]

  -- Determine if this player has a table of vanity backs.
  local vanityBackTable = vanityBacks[playerReference.steam_name] or vanityBacks[playerReference.steam_id] or nil

  -- If this player has a vanity back set for this character, override the predetermined back.
  if vanityBackTable != nil then
    backURL = vanityBackTable[deckName] or backURL
  end

  -- Meme cardback added for April Fool's 2021.
  if math.random(1,20) == 1 then
    backURL = [[https://i.imgur.com/wTx8sqt.png]]
  end

  -- Each UNLOCKED costume, including the primary one, will be inserted in the costumeTable.
  local costumeTable = {}

  -- The index of the costumeTable entry that has the highest costumePriority.
  local highestCostumePriorityIndex = 1

  -- This got a little more complicated because we want to be able to override which State is the default.
  costumeTable[1] = {
    priority = 1,
    jsonParams = {
      charEntry       = charTable[deckName],
      deckName        = deckName,
      deckDescription = deckDescription,
      deckList        = deckList,
      deckNormals     = charTable[deckName].normals,
      deckNormalsSet  = charTable[deckName].normalsSet,
      deckNormalsDeck = charTable[deckName].normalsDeck,
      player          = playerReference,
      alternate       = alternate,
      cardColor       = cardColor,
      backURL         = backURL,
    },
  }

  --[=[
    The combined JSON is made by concatenating:
    primary costume JSON
        (determined once we know which costume has the highest priority)
    combinedJSONpostCharacter
        (defined below; starts the States value)
    alternate costume JSONs
        (if more than one alternate costume, separate with comma and linebreak)
    combinedJSONpostCostumes
        (defined below; ends the States value and closes the JSON properly)
  --]=]
  local combinedJSONpostCharacter = [[,
  "States": {
]]
  local combinedJSONpostCostumes = [[
  }
}
]]


  -- Costume handling.
  if charTable[deckName].costumes != nil then
    --debugLog{" 1 or more costumes", 0}
    local unlockedCostumeCount = 0

    -- Loop through the costumes and add them to the costume table.
    for costumeIndex,thisCostume in ipairs(charTable[deckName].costumes) do
      -- This variable checks whether the costume is "unlocked" for the player.
      local isUnlocked = true

      -- First, if this costume has a password, confirm that it has been unlocked.
      if thisCostume.costumePassword != nil then
        isUnlocked = false
        local codeLength = string.len(thisCostume.costumePassword)

        -- Check only the END of the player's entered password.
        if string.sub(passwordEntries[playerReference.steam_id], -1*codeLength) == thisCostume.costumePassword then
          isUnlocked = true
        end -- end password comparison
      end -- end password check

      -- Then, if this costume has a "costumeOwner" table, confirm that the spawning player is one of the owners.
      if isUnlocked == true and thisCostume.costumeOwner != nil then
        isUnlocked = false
        -- Checks each entry in the "costumeOwner" table.
        for ownerIndex,thisOwner in ipairs(thisCostume.costumeOwner) do
          -- Checks against name OR Steam ID.
          if playerReference.steam_name == thisOwner or playerReference.steam_id == thisOwner then
            isUnlocked = true
          end -- finish checking this entry in the costumeOwner table
        end -- finish checking costumeOwner table
      end -- finish check for costumeOwner table

      if isUnlocked == true then
        unlockedCostumeCount = unlockedCostumeCount+1
        -- costumePriority determines which costumes override each other for the default. Higher is "stronger".
        -- The default costume has a priority of 1, meaning this must be 1 or higher to override default.
        local costumePriority = thisCostume.costumePriority or 0

        -- Some costumes may have a different priority when not left-clicked.
        if alternate == true then
          costumePriority = thisCostume.alternatePriority or costumePriority
        end

        -- If this costume is registered as a "favorite" for a specific player, check for that.
        if thisCostume.costumeFavorite != nil then
          -- Check each entry in the costumeFavorite table.
          for ownerFavoriteIndex,thisOwnerFavorite in ipairs(thisCostume.costumeFavorite) do
            -- Checks against name OR Steam ID.
            if playerReference.steam_name == thisOwnerFavorite or playerReference.steam_id == thisOwnerFavorite then
              costumePriority = 99
            end -- finish checking this entry in costumeFavorite
          end -- finish checking costumeFavorite table
        end -- finish checking favorite owners

        -- If there's a password which prioritizes this costume (rather than unlocking it), check for that.
        if thisCostume.costumePasswordFavorite != nil then
          local codeLength = string.len(thisCostume.costumePasswordFavorite)

          -- Check only the END of the player's entered password.
          if string.sub(passwordEntries[playerReference.steam_id], -1*codeLength) == thisCostume.costumePasswordFavorite then
            costumePriority = 98
          end -- end password comparison
        end

        --[=[
          If this costume's priority is equal to or greater than the priority of the current highest-priority costume,
          set the highestCostumePriorityIndex (i.e., the index of the costume with the highest priority) to its index in the costume table.
        --]=]
        if costumePriority >= costumeTable[highestCostumePriorityIndex].priority then
          --debugLog{"updating highest-priority costume: "..costumePriority, 1}
          -- The +1 here is to account for the costumeTable including the primary costume as well as alternates.
          highestCostumePriorityIndex = unlockedCostumeCount+1
        end

        -- If this player has a vanity back set for this character, override the predetermined back.
        local costumeBackURL = backURL
        if thisCostume.costumeAttackBack != nil then
          costumeBackURL = thisCostume.costumeAttackBack
        end
        if vanityBackTable != nil then
          if vanityBackTable[thisCostume.costumeName] != nil then
            costumeBackURL = vanityBackTable[thisCostume.costumeName]
          end
        end

        --debugLog{"costumeBackURL: "..costumeBackURL, 1}
        --debugLog{"costumeAttackBack: "..thisCostume.costumeAttackBack}

        -- If the costume is set to use a different Normals style (e.g., Seventh Cross), that overrides the default.
        local costumeNormals = charTable[deckName].normals
        if thisCostume.costumeNormals != nil then
          costumeNormals = thisCostume.costumeNormals
        end

        -- I can't currently think of a reason that a costume would use a different set of Normals (e.g., UNNormals) than the base character.
        -- If that ever happens, I can override this variable's value by adding some code after it is set.
        local costumeNormalsSet = charTable[deckName].normalsSet

        --debugLog{"inserting unlockedCostumeCount: "..unlockedCostumeCount+1, 1, {1,0.4,0.4}}
        costumeTable[unlockedCostumeCount+1] = {
          priority = costumePriority,
          jsonParams = {
            charEntry       = charTable[deckName],
            deckName        = thisCostume.costumeName,
            deckDescription = thisCostume.costumeDescription,
            deckList        = thisCostume.costumeDeck,
            deckNormals     = costumeNormals,
            deckNormalsSet  = costumeNormalsSet,
            deckNormalsDeck = thisCostume.costumeNormalsDeck,
            player          = playerReference,
            alternate       = alternate,
            cardColor       = thisCostume.costumeColor or cardColor,
            backURL         = costumeBackURL,
            --lockBag         = lockBag,
          },
        }

        --debugLog{"combinedJSON UNLOCKED", 4, {0,0.8,0.7}}
        --debugLog{combinedJSON, 4, {0,0.8,0.7}}
      end -- end "if isUnlocked == true"
    end -- end costume loop
  end -- end costume handling

  -- Set the main character JSON to the JSON of the highest-priority costume.
  local characterParams = costumeTable[highestCostumePriorityIndex].jsonParams
  -- Lock the bag that will be spawned in as the active State to prevent unwanted interactions.
  -- (It gets unlocked by the callback function, deckToHand.)
  characterParams.lockBag = "true"
  local characterJSON,alternateUsed,alternateExists = getBagJSON(characterParams)
  table.remove(costumeTable, highestCostumePriorityIndex)

  -- Loop through the additional (non-primary) costumes to add them as additional states.
  local costumeCount = 0
  local costumeJSON = [[]]
  for additionalCostumeIndex,thisCostume in ipairs(costumeTable) do
    --debugLog{"additionalCostumeIndex: "..additionalCostumeIndex, 2}
    --[=[
      The +1 is here because additional States start indexed at 2.
      TTS infers the current state based on which number is missing from the list of states.
      In other words, if there's one State and it's listed as 1, then the CURRENT State becomes State 2.
      If there's one State and it's listed as 4, then the current State is registered as State 1, and States 2 and 3 are empty, but still in the list.
      It's real jank.
    --]=]
    local costumeState = additionalCostumeIndex+1
    local costumeParams = costumeTable[additionalCostumeIndex].jsonParams

    -- Costumes created as additional States shouldn't be locked (character bags are only locked to prevent interactions on spawn).
    costumeParams.lockBag = "false"

    -- If there's at least one other costume, they need to be separated by commas per JSON specs.
    if costumeCount != 0 then
      --debugLog{"   comma separating",3,{1,1,0}}
      costumeJSON = costumeJSON..[[,
      ]]
    end -- end "if costumeCount != 0"

    costumeJSON = costumeJSON..[["]]..costumeState..[[": ]]..getBagJSON(costumeParams)..[[
    }
]]
    costumeCount = costumeCount+1
  end -- end additional costume loop

  -- Create the final combined JSON string for the bag to be spawned.
  local combinedJSON = characterJSON..combinedJSONpostCharacter..costumeJSON..combinedJSONpostCostumes
  --debugLog{ " COMBINED JSON STRING: "..combinedJSON, 5, {1,0,1}}

  if costumeCount > 0 then
    playerReference.broadcast([=[[i]~ Palette Swap: Right-click the bag and choose "State"! ~[/i]]=])
  end

  -- Actually spawn the bag.
  if deckIDList != [[]] or referenceIDList != [[]] or separateIDList != [[]] then
    --debugLog{ " playerHandTransform.position: "..playerHandTransform.position.x..", "..playerHandTransform.position.y..", "..playerHandTransform.position.z, 3}
    spawnObjectJSON({
      json = combinedJSON,
      position = playerHandTransform.position,
      callback_function = function(obj) deckToHand(obj, futureName, playerReference.color) end,
    })
    --debugLog{ "Spawning character bag!", 0, {0.2, 1, 0.2} }
    --local broadcastColor = Color[player.color]
    local broadcastColor = {}
    broadcastColor[1] = cardColor[1]+0.5
    broadcastColor[2] = cardColor[2]+0.5
    broadcastColor[3] = cardColor[3]+0.5
    if playerReference.color != "Black" then
      if alternateUsed == false and alternateExists == true then
        playerReference.broadcast(deckName..[[ + references added to your hand!
(For alternative cosmetics, right-click instead!)]], broadcastColor)
      else
        playerReference.broadcast(deckName..[[ + references added to your hand!]], broadcastColor)
      end
      --Player[player.color].pingTable(playerHandTransform.position)
    end
  end
end -- end spawnDeck



function debugLog(params)
  local debugText = params[1] or "<empty debug call>"
  local debugImportance = params[2] or 0
  local debugColor = params[3] or {0,1,0}
  --debugText = debugText or "<empty debug call>"
  --debugImportance = debugImportance or 0
  --debugColor = debugColor or {1,1,1}
  local debugFlag = Global.getVar("debugFlag") or false
  local debugLevel = Global.getVar("debugLevel") or 1
  if debugFlag == true and debugLevel >= debugImportance then
    printToAll(debugText, debugColor)
  end
end



function uiClick_Random(player, value, id)
  if _G["activeSearch"..player.color] != nil then
    return
  end
  if player.color == [[Grey]] then
    player.broadcast([[Spectators cannot spawn characters.]])
    return
  end
  --debugLog{ "uiClick_Random clicked by "..player.color, 0 }
  --debugLog{ "   value: "..value, 3 }
  --debugLog{ "      id: "..id, 3 }
  --local clickedObject = getObjectFromGUID('4c8428')
  local deckList, deckNickname = getRandomDeck(id, player)
  --debugLog{ "   deckNickname: "..deckNickname, 1, { 1, 1, 0 } }

  -- If NOT clicked with the left mouse button, alternate mode is on.
  local alternate = false
  if value != "-1" then
    --debugLog{ "   alternate mode is on", 1, {0, 1, 1} }
    alternate = true
  end

  spawnDeck({ deckName = deckNickname, deckList = deckList, player = player, alternate = alternate })
end

function deckToHand(obj, name, color)
  --[=[
  if Player[color].getHandTransform() == nil then
    obj.setLock(false)
    return
  end
  local playerHandTransform = Player[color].getHandTransform()
  local playerHandRotation = playerHandTransform.rotation
  local playerHandPosition = playerHandTransform.position
  obj.setPositionSmooth({playerHandPosition.x, playerHandPosition.y, playerHandPosition.z}, false, true)
  obj.setRotation({x = playerHandRotation.x, y = 180+playerHandRotation.y, z = playerHandRotation.z,})
  --]=]
  obj.setLock(false)
end



function getBagJSON(params)
  local debugLog        = debugLog
  local charEntry       = params.charEntry
  local deckName        = params.deckName
  local deckDescription = params.deckDescription or charTable[deckName].deckDescription or [[]] -- Usually nil.
  local deckList        = params.deckList
  local normalsName     = params.deckNormals
  local normalsSet      = params.deckNormalsSet or [[Normals]]
  local normalsDeck     = params.deckNormalsDeck
  local player          = params.player
  local alternate       = params.alternate or false
  local lockBag         = params.lockBag or "true"

  local characterNormalsScript = charEntry.normalsScript or [[]]

  local cardColor = {}
  cardColor[1] = params.cardColor[1] or 0.713235259
  cardColor[2] = params.cardColor[2] or 0.713235259
  cardColor[3] = params.cardColor[3] or 0.713235259
  cardColor[4] = params.cardColor[4] or 1

  local backURL = params.backURL or [[https://i.imgur.com/igYZhPh.png]]

  -- Use alternate attack back, if available, in alternate mode.
  -- This doesn't interact with alternateUsed or alternateExists because it's just the attack back.
  if alternate == true and charEntry.altattackBack != nil then
    backURL = charEntry.altattackBack
  end

  -- The clicks are caught by UI elements, which Grey actually CAN interact with.
  -- Nobody actually expects this, so we should ignore Grey's clicks.
  if player.color == "Grey" then return end

  local screenRotation = selectScreen.getRotation()
  local xPositionOffset = 0
  local zPositionOffset = 0
  local yPositionOffset = 0
  local facingFactor = 1
  if screenRotation.z >= 90 and screenRotation.z < 270 then
    facingFactor = -1
  end

  local charPosition = {}
  charPosition.x = 0
  charPosition.y = 0
  charPosition.z = 0

  if charEntry.position != nil then
    charPosition.x = charEntry.position.x or 0
    charPosition.y = charEntry.position.y or 0
    charPosition.z = charEntry.position.z or 0
  end

  if screenRotation.y >= 45 and screenRotation.y < 135 then
    xPositionOffset = -1.1*facingFactor*charPosition.z
    yPositionOffset = charPosition.y
    zPositionOffset = -1.1*charPosition.x
  elseif screenRotation.y >= 135 and screenRotation.y < 225 then
    xPositionOffset = -1.1*facingFactor*charPosition.x
    yPositionOffset = facingFactor*charPosition.y
    zPositionOffset = 1.1*charPosition.z
  elseif screenRotation.y >= 225 and screenRotation.y < 315 then
    xPositionOffset = 1.1*facingFactor*charPosition.z
    yPositionOffset = facingFactor*charPosition.y
    zPositionOffset = 1.1*charPosition.x
  elseif screenRotation.y >= 315 or screenRotation.y < 45 then
    xPositionOffset = 1.1*facingFactor*charPosition.x
    yPositionOffset = facingFactor*charPosition.y
    zPositionOffset = -1.1*charPosition.z
  end

  local playerHandTransform = Player[player.color].getHandTransform() or {
    position = {
      x = xPositionOffset + selectScreen.getPosition().x,
      y = 10 + yPositionOffset + selectScreen.getPosition().y,
      z = zPositionOffset + selectScreen.getPosition().z,
    },
    rotation = selectScreen.getRotation(),
  }
  local bagTransformString = [[{
    "posX": ]]..playerHandTransform.position.x..[[,
    "posY": ]]..playerHandTransform.position.y..[[,
    "posZ": ]]..playerHandTransform.position.z..[[,
    "scaleX": 0.9,
    "scaleY": 0.6,
    "scaleZ": 0.9,
  }]]
  local transformFacingYou = {
    scaleX = 1.25,
    scaleY = 1.0,
    scaleZ = 1.25,
    rotX = 0,
    rotY = (playerHandTransform.rotation.y+180),
    rotZ = 0,
  }
  local transformFacingAway = {
    scaleX = 1.25,
    scaleY = 1.0,
    scaleZ = 1.25,
    rotX = 0,
    rotY = (playerHandTransform.rotation.y),
    rotZ = 0,
  }
  local transformStringFacingYou = [[{
    "scaleX": "]]..transformFacingYou.scaleX..[[",
    "scaleY": "]]..transformFacingYou.scaleY..[[",
    "scaleZ": "]]..transformFacingYou.scaleZ..[[",
    "rotX": "]]..transformFacingYou.rotX..[[",
    "rotY": "]]..transformFacingYou.rotY..[[",
    "rotZ": "]]..transformFacingYou.rotZ..[[",
  }]]
  local transformStringFacingAway = [[{
    "scaleX": "]]..transformFacingAway.scaleX..[[",
    "scaleY": "]]..transformFacingAway.scaleY..[[",
    "scaleZ": "]]..transformFacingAway.scaleZ..[[",
    "rotX": "]]..transformFacingAway.rotX..[[",
    "rotY": "]]..transformFacingAway.rotY..[[",
    "rotZ": "]]..transformFacingAway.rotZ..[[",
  }]]

  local currentNormals = _G["normals"..player.color] or "Default"
  local characterNormals = [[Seventh Cross]]

  debugLog{ " current normalsSet: "..normalsSet, 1 }
  if normalsName != nil then
    debugLog{"setting characterNormals to normalsName: "..normalsName, 1}
    characterNormals = normalsName
  end

  -- If the normals are set to Default (Alternate) and there is an entry for the alternative version of the character's default Normals...
  if currentNormals == "Default (Alternate)" and normalsSheets[characterNormals.." (Alternate)"] != nil then
    -- ... and there is a sub-entry corresponding to the normalsSet in use, set the normals to those normals plus " (Alternate)"
    if normalsSheets[characterNormals.." (Alternate)"][normalsSet] != nil then
      currentNormals = characterNormals.." (Alternate)"
    end
  end

  -- If the normals are set to Default or (still) set to Default (Alternate), they should use the character's actual default.
  if currentNormals == "Default" or currentNormals == "Default (Alternate)" then
    currentNormals = characterNormals
  end

  -- If non-alternate Normals are in use and there are alternates available...
  if string.sub(currentNormals, -12) != " (Alternate)" and normalsSheets[characterNormals.." (Alternate)"] != nil then
    -- ... and there is a sub-entry corresponding to the normalsSet in use, inform the player that there are reskins available.
    if normalsSheets[characterNormals.." (Alternate)"][normalsSet] != nil then
      player.print("Reskinned Normals available (right-click the Normal toggle to select).", {0.8, 0.8, 0.8} )
    end
  end

  -- If the character's Normals set just doesn't exist at all, default to Seventh Cross.
  if normalsSheets[currentNormals] == nil then
    debugLog{ " couldn't find Normals: "..currentNormals, 1}
    currentNormals = [[Seventh Cross]]
  end

  --debugLog{ " printing table: normalsSet", 3}
  --printToAll(printTable(normalsSheets[currentNormals][normalsSet]))

  --debugLog{ " printing table: currentNormals", 3}
  --printToAll(printTable(normalsSheets[currentNormals]))

  -- If the selected Normals have no appropriate sub-entry for the normalsSet in use...
  if normalsSheets[currentNormals][normalsSet] == nil then
    debugLog{ "  no appropriate sub-entry", 1, {1,1,0}}

    -- If the selected Normals are alternate, check for a sub-entry for the base version.
    local baseNormals = currentNormals
    if string.sub(currentNormals, -12) == " (Alternate)" then
       baseNormals = string.sub(currentNormals, 1, (string.len(currentNormals)-12))
    end
